Rust removers contain corrosive chemicals that can cause damage to the GI tract, leading to esophageal strictures as a long-term complication. The other options listed are less likely to be seen in this patient, especially considering her age.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The ingestion of rust remover suggests a corrosive injury to the esophagus, which can lead to scarring and stricture formation in the long term. Esophageal webs are associated with iron deficiency anemia, and Mallory-Weiss tears are typically caused by forceful vomiting. Oral cavity cancer is not a typical complication of corrosive ingestion.

Esophageal webs, Mallory-Weiss tears, and oral cavity cancer are not expected complications of a chemical ingestion.

Rust removers are usually acidic, and ingestion can cause chemical burns and scarring in the esophagus, leading to esophageal strictures as a long-term complication. Esophageal webs typically occur in adults with iron-deficiency anemia. Mallory-Weiss tears are caused by forceful vomiting and are usually self-limited. Oral cavity cancer is not a likely complication of ingestion of rust remover.

Rust remover typically contains hydrofluoric acid which can cause severe esophageal injury and scarring leading to strictures as a long-term complication. Esophageal webs are more common in disorders such as Plummer-Vinson syndrome, Mallory-Weiss tears typically occur due to excessive vomiting, and oral cavity cancer is not a likely complication of acute ingestion of rust remover.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The ingestion of rust remover can cause chemical burns and damage the lining of the esophagus, leading to scarring and strictures. Esophageal webs are thin membranes that can obstruct the esophagus, but they are typically due to genetic disorders or vitamin deficiencies rather than chemical ingestion. Mallory-Weiss tears are lacerations of the lower end of the esophagus that can cause bleeding, but they are usually due to forceful vomiting or retching rather than chemical ingestion. Oral cavity cancer is not a likely complication of this acute ingestion.

This can result in esophageal strictures as a long-term complication. Esophageal webs are also an option, but they are less common. Mallory-Weiss tears and oral cavity cancer are not likely long-term complications of this ingestion.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The ingestion of a rust remover can cause caustic injury to the esophagus. Symptoms such as pain with swallowing, mild erythema of the epiglottis and heavy salivation are consistent with this diagnosis. Esophageal strictures are a possible long-term complication, as the injury can lead to scarring or narrowing of the esophagus. Esophageal webs may also occur, but they are a less common complication. Mallory-Weiss tears and oral cavity cancer are not typically associated with caustic ingestion.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Rust removers contain hydrochloric acid, which can cause corrosive injury to the esophagus. The most likely long-term complication is the development of esophageal strictures, which can lead to difficulty swallowing or even complete obstruction.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Rust remover is typically composed of strong acids or alkaline substances that can lead to chemical burns and tissue damage in the upper digestive tract. This damage can result in esophageal strictures, which is the narrowing of the esophagus that may cause difficulty swallowing and food impaction. Esophageal webs are thin membranes that may form across the upper part of the esophagus due to various causes, but not typically as a result of chemical ingestion. Mallory-Weiss tears refer to tears in the mucosa at the gastroesophageal junction or lower esophagus due to forceful vomiting or retching, which is not reported in this case. Oral cavity cancer is unlikely to be a long-term complication of this acute exposure.
